IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - A growing body of research deals with congruence and incongruence between supervisors' and subordinates' perception and subsequent effects on outcome variables for organizations and individuals. The results of these studies have indicated positive relationships between congruence and (1) supervisors' evaluations of subordinates (Green, 1972; Miles, 1964; Wexley, Alexander, Greenwalt,  (2) subordinates' satisfaction and morale (Brown  Greene, 1972; Wexley et al., 1980); (3) subordinates' liking for supervisors (Triandis, 1959); (4) quality of relationships between supervisors and subordinates (Green  and (5) subordinates' satisfaction with communication (Hatfield  Wexley et al., 1980). The purpose of this study is to examine a relationship between congruence and communication satisfaction to determine if it is primarily a function of congruence, or of one or the other of the components of congruence. This study does not seek to replicate earlier perceptual congruence research, but rather to investigate the parsimony of D statistics in the context of a perceptual congruence study.
AB  - A growing body of research deals with congruence and incongruence between supervisors' and subordinates' perception and subsequent effects on outcome variables for organizations and individuals. The results of these studies have indicated positive relationships between congruence and (1) supervisors' evaluations of subordinates (Green, 1972; Miles, 1964; Wexley, Alexander, Greenwalt,  (2) subordinates' satisfaction and morale (Brown  Greene, 1972; Wexley et al., 1980); (3) subordinates' liking for supervisors (Triandis, 1959); (4) quality of relationships between supervisors and subordinates (Green  and (5) subordinates' satisfaction with communication (Hatfield  Wexley et al., 1980). The purpose of this study is to examine a relationship between congruence and communication satisfaction to determine if it is primarily a function of congruence, or of one or the other of the components of congruence. This study does not seek to replicate earlier perceptual congruence research, but rather to investigate the parsimony of D statistics in the context of a perceptual congruence study.
