TY  - JOUR
T1  - Assessing the Effects of Industrial Relations Systems and Efforts to Improve the Quality of Working Life on Organizational Effectiveness
AU  - Katz, Harry C.
AU  - Kochan, Thomas A.
AU  - Weber, Mark R.
Y1  - 1985/09/01
PY  - 1985
DA  - 1985/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256111
DO  - 10.5465/256111
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 509
EP  - 526
VL  - 28
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This study assesses the relationships among characteristics of industrial relations systems, efforts to improve the quality of working life, and selected measures of organizational effectiveness in 25 manufacturing plants belonging to one company. On the basis of both research from organizational behavior and industrial relations, the paper offers the proposition that industrial relations systems affect organizational effectiveness through two channels. The empirical results show (1) strong evidence of an association between measures of the performance of industrial relations systems and economic performance, and (2) evidence that efforts to improve quality of working life have little impact on economic performance.
AB  - This study assesses the relationships among characteristics of industrial relations systems, efforts to improve the quality of working life, and selected measures of organizational effectiveness in 25 manufacturing plants belonging to one company. On the basis of both research from organizational behavior and industrial relations, the paper offers the proposition that industrial relations systems affect organizational effectiveness through two channels. The empirical results show (1) strong evidence of an association between measures of the performance of industrial relations systems and economic performance, and (2) evidence that efforts to improve quality of working life have little impact on economic performance.
